Here is a Java solution using a while loop:

```java 
class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if(n > 1)
            while(n % 3 == 0) n /= 3;

        return n == 1;
    }
}
```

In this code, if n > 1, we keep dividing n by 3 as long as its divisible (n % 3 == 0). In the end, if the result n becomes 1, it's a power of 3. Otherwise, it's not a power of 3.

As for the follow-up, we can take advantage of the fact that in Java the max value that Integer can reach is `2147483647`, which is 3^19. So, we can return `n > 0 && 1162261467 % n == 0`.

Here's the non-loop solution using this approach:

```java 
class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        return n > 0 && 1162261467 % n == 0;
    }
}
```

This code checks if the number is greater than 0 (since no negative number can be a power of 3) and if 1162261467 (which is 3^19) is divisible by n. This guarantees that n is a power of 3.
This approach works because 1162261467 is the maximum power of 3 that integer can hold, and since 3 is a prime number, 1162261467 will only have factors that are the power of 3.

