```java
public class Main {

    static int LCS(String s1, String s2) {
        int len1 = s1.length();
        int len2 = s2.length();

        // Create a table to store lengths of longest common subsequences for substrings
        int[][] memo = new int[len1+1][len2+1];

        // Fill memo[][] from bottom up
        for (int i=len1-1; i>=0; i--) {
            for (int j=len2-1; j>=0; j--) {
                if (s1.charAt(i) == s2.charAt(j)) {
                    memo[i][j] = memo[i+1][j+1]+1;
                }
                else {
                    memo[i][j] = Math.max(memo[i+1][j], memo[i][j+1]);
                }
            }
        }
        return memo[0][0];
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String s1 = "ABCDGH";
        String s2 = "AEDFHR";
        System.out.println("Length of LCS is " + LCS(s1, s2));
    }
}
```

In the above code, the `LCS` method calculates the length of the longest common subsequence of two strings. It uses a two-dimensional array `memo` to store the lengths of longest common subsequences for the substrings of `s1` and `s2`. The length of the longest common subsequence for `s1` and `s2` is then located in `memo[0][0]`.

